        <p class="article-para-text">Let‚Äôs be real. HSC admission season in Bangladesh feels like a mix of panic, pressure, and your aunt asking ‚ÄúWhich college e porbi?‚Äù for the tenth time. It‚Äôs confusing, weirdly intense, and unless you‚Äôve got a cousin who just went through it, no one seems to explain it properly.</p>
        <p class="article-para-text">So here‚Äôs a clear, honest, and straight-to-the-point guide that helps. Whether you‚Äôre aiming for Rajuk, Viqarunnisa, or Dhaka College, or just want to get into a solid college and start fresh, this is for you.</p>
  
        <h2 id="step1">Step 1: Know What You‚Äôre Applying For</h2>
        <p class="article-para-text">Before anything else, figure out what you need to get in. Most colleges (especially top ones) want:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>GPA 5.00 if you‚Äôre applying to science</li>
          <li>A decent GPA (4.5+ usually safe) for commerce or humanities</li>
          <li>Some ask for subject-specific grades especially in math or science</li>
        </ul>
        <p class="article-para-text">You‚Äôll need:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>SSC transcript and certificate</li>
          <li>Birth certificate</li>
          <li>Recent passport-sized photos</li>
          <li>Mobile number used during SSC registration</li>
          <li>Guardian‚Äôs NID (sometimes asked during verification)</li>
        </ul>
        <p class="article-para-text"><strong>Pro tip:</strong> Scan everything. Keep it in your phone and Google Drive. Losing the original the night before the deadline = pain.</p>
  
        <h2 id="step2">Step 2: Decide Which Colleges to Aim For</h2>
        <p class="article-para-text">There are two types of colleges when it comes to admission:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Merit-based colleges via the government portal ‚Äî like Rajuk, Viqarunnisa, Dhaka College, Holy Cross, Ideal, etc.</li>
          <li>Institutions like Notre Dame & Holy Cross ‚Äî they run separate admission processes with their own forms & tests.</li>
        </ul>
        <p class="article-para-text">So don‚Äôt put Notre Dame in your government preference list ‚Äî it won‚Äôt work. If you‚Äôre applying to these colleges, check their websites or Facebook pages directly.</p>
        <p class="article-para-text">For the government portal, you‚Äôll list up to 10 choices ‚Äî rank them smartly:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>2‚Äì3 dream colleges</li>
          <li>4‚Äì5 mid-tier options</li>
          <li>2‚Äì3 backups (realistic safety net)</li>
        </ul>
  
        <h2 id="step3">Step 3: Make a Study Plan</h2>
        <p class="article-para-text">Look, you don‚Äôt need a bullet journal or 4-color highlighters. Just write down:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>What subjects you're struggling with</li>
          <li>Topics you want to revise before college starts</li>
          <li>Entrance prep (if you're applying to Notre Dame, Holy Cross, etc.)</li>
        </ul>
        <p class="article-para-text">If you‚Äôre still in ‚Äúpost-SSC chill mode,‚Äù that‚Äôs fine. But HSC isn‚Äôt slow-paced. Having a headstart makes life easier later.</p>
  
        <h2 id="step4">Step 4: Online Form? Here‚Äôs What Actually Matters</h2>
        <p class="article-para-text">If you‚Äôre going through <code>xiclassadmission.gov.bd</code>, here‚Äôs how it works:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Choose up to 10 colleges</li>
          <li>Rank them carefully</li>
          <li>Submit with a small fee via bKash/Nagad</li>
          <li>Wait for your result (they‚Äôll notify you via SMS)</li>
        </ul>
        <p class="article-para-text">Things to keep in mind:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Choose shift wisely (morning/evening) ‚Äî some colleges have separate merit lists</li>
          <li>Save your transaction ID</li>
          <li>Don‚Äôt panic if you don‚Äôt get your top choice ‚Äî there are multiple phases for migration and re-application</li>
        </ul>
        <p class="article-para-text">üéØ <strong>Again:</strong> Notre Dame, Holy Cross, etc. do not use this process. You need to collect and submit their form separately.</p>
  
        <h2 id="step5">Step 5: Prep for Mini Admission Tests (If Needed)</h2>
        <p class="article-para-text">Colleges like Notre Dame, Holy Cross, and a few others might ask for small written tests, usually based on SSC-level English and general knowledge.</p>
        <p class="article-para-text">So brush up on:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Basic English grammar and comprehension</li>
          <li>Current events and GK</li>
          <li>Short essay or paragraph writing</li>
        </ul>
        <p class="article-para-text">If you‚Äôve taken board exams, you‚Äôre more than ready. You just need to dust off the brain cells and review a little.</p>
  
        <h2 id="step6">Step 6: Plan for Fees (Yeah, It Adds Up Fast)</h2>
        <p class="article-para-text">HSC admission isn‚Äôt super expensive, but the little things add up:</p>
        <ul>
